	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=8&mid=101664083479484>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101664083479484>RE: Regarding your post</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101664083479484#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Mar 20th 11:16 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=92601><span id=Sage>Feldaer</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>207 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.21]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I was following you, until you got to the prices for lightstones. Merchants will pay about 3-4pp for a greater lightstone, and just over 1 pp for a lightstone. to get the most cash from greater lightstones (8-9pp) you need to go to north karana, and trade the GLS for a concordance of research, then sell it back to the gypsy who gives it to you. To get the concordance, you must give, not sell, the GLS.<br><br>Also, At least on my server (rodcet nife), these are the common prices for pelts/silks:<br><br>Spiderling silk - 5pp per stack (Don't waste these on bandages, unless someone is offering to buy them, they are hard to sell, you'll get more from blacksmiths who want them for padding.)<br>Silk thread (combine 2 spiderling silks in a tailoring kit) - 10pp per stack<br>Spider - 10pp per stack<br>Silk swatches (Combine 2 spider silks in a tailoring kit) - 20pp per stack<br>LQ cat/wolf/bear pelts - 20pp per stack<br>MQ cat/wolf/bear - 40pp per stack<br>HQ cat/wolf - 80pp per stack<br>HQ bear - 40pp EACH PELT<br><br>Now, since the original poster indicated he had little cash, and therefore, presumably also little armor, I should point out that you can make nice patchwork armor from the ruined wolf and cat pelts. Elves can wear either one, although the wolf is better, as it weighs less.<br><br>One of your first puchases should be a small tailoring kit. ALWAYS combine your silks to make threads and swatches, as it never fails, and can take you up to about lvl 20 in skill, without wasting your training points. Then you can start making some patchwork armor (combine one ruined pelt and the appropriate pattern, bought from vendors). <br><br>Once you get better at tailoring, you can begin making studded leather, which is a big upgrade from the patchwork, and you can actually sell a bit of this. Also, you can make the cured silk, which sells ok to new monks, and raw silk, which is a slow seller, but might make you some cash from casters. Once you reach about 80 skill, you can start making tailored backpacks, and then the money rolls in. they sell for 100pp or more each. I rarely fail at 88 skill.</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
